    "notes_on_text": [
      {
        "title": "Indefinite Pronouns with -one, -thing, -where",
        "content": "In English, compound words formed with 'some, any, no, every' and '-one, -body, -thing, -where' act as pronouns. They are called indefinite pronouns because they do not refer to a specific person or thing. For example, 'Isn't there anyone at home?' (家里没人吗?) uses 'anyone' in a question. 'I'm sure there's no one at home.' (肯定家里没有人。) uses 'no one' in a negative statement. 'Look! Everyone's in the garden.' (瞧!大家都在花园里。) uses 'everyone' to refer to all people."
      },
      {
        "title": "The use of 'nice and...'",
        "content": "The phrase 'nice and...' is used before an adjective or adverb to strengthen its meaning. It usually carries a positive connotation, but can sometimes be used negatively. For example, 'It's nice and warm out here.' (这外面挺暖和。) means it's very warm and pleasant."
      },
      {
        "title": "'There's none left.'",
        "content": "The phrase 'There's none left.' (一点儿都没剩下。) means that nothing remains. In this sentence, 'left' is a past participle modifying 'none'."
      }
    ],
    "grammar_sections": [
      {
        "title": "Indefinite Pronouns: -one, -body, -thing, -where compounds",
        "explanation": "This lesson focuses on indefinite pronouns formed by combining 'every', 'no', 'any', and 'some' with suffixes like '-one', '-body', '-thing', and '-where'. These pronouns refer to unspecified people, things, or places. \n\n- **Every- compounds (everyone, everybody, everything, everywhere)**: Refer to all members of a group or all of something. Used in affirmative statements.\n  *Example: Everyone is asleep. (每个人都睡着了。)\n\n- **No- compounds (no one, nobody, nothing, nowhere)**: Refer to the absence of people, things, or places. Used in affirmative sentences to convey a negative meaning.\n  *Example: There's no one at home. (家里没有人。)\n\n- **Any- compounds (anyone, anybody, anything, anywhere)**: Primarily used in questions and negative statements. Can also be used in affirmative statements with a meaning of 'it doesn't matter who/what/where'.\n  *Example: Is there anyone at home? (家里有人吗?)\n  *Example: I couldn't find my pen anywhere. (我哪里也找不到我的钢笔。)\n\n- **Some- compounds (someone, somebody, something, somewhere)**: Primarily used in affirmative statements and offers/requests (which are technically questions but expect a 'yes' answer).\n  *Example: There's someone in the garden. (花园里有某人。)\n  *Example: Have some beer! (喝点啤酒吧!)",
